04834nam a22005175i 9780226298719DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226298719  a(DE-B1597)524376  a(OCoLC)922581679  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQC983b.D26 2016 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a551.632231 aDaipha, Phaedra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMasters of Uncertainty :bWeather Forecasters and the Quest for Ground Truth /cPhaedra Daipha. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b1 halftone, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Decision Making under Uncertainty -- t1. The Weather Prediction Enterprise -- t2. Working the Weather: A Shift in the Life of a Weather Forecaster -- t3. Distilling Complexity: Atmospheric Indeterminacy and the Culture of Disciplined Improvisation -- t4. Managing Risk: The Trials and Tribulations of Hazardous Weather Forecasting -- t5. Anticipating the Future: Temporal Regimes of Meteorological Decision Making -- t6. Whose Weather Is It Anyway? From the Production to the Consumption of Decisions -- t7. Toward a Sociology of Decision Making -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThough we commonly make them the butt of our jokes, weather forecasters are in fact exceptionally good at managing uncertainty. They consistently do a better job calibrating their performance than stockbrokers, physicians, or other decision-making experts precisely because they receive feedback on their decisions in near real time. Following forecasters in their quest for truth and accuracy, therefore, holds the key to the analytically elusive process of decision making as it actually happens. In Masters of Uncertainty, Phaedra Daipha develops a new conceptual framework for the process of decision making, after spending years immersed in the life of a northeastern office of the National Weather Service. Arguing that predicting the weather will always be more craft than science, Daipha shows how forecasters have made a virtue of the unpredictability of the weather. Impressive data infrastructures and powerful computer models are still only a substitute for the real thing outside, and so forecasters also enlist improvisational collage techniques and an omnivorous appetite for information to create a locally meaningful forecast on their computer screens. Intent on capturing decision making in action, Daipha takes the reader through engrossing firsthand accounts of several forecasting episodes (hits and misses) and offers a rare fly-on-the-wall insight into the process and challenges of producing meteorological predictions come rain or come shine. Combining rich detail with lucid argument, Masters of Uncertainty advances a theory of decision making that foregrounds the pragmatic and situated nature of expert cognition and casts into new light how we make decisions in the digital age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aWeather forecasting - Decision making. 0aWeather forecastingxDecision making. 0aWeather forecastingzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  auncertainty, weather, sociology, social studies, forecasters, truth, accuracy, decision making, national service, meteorology, predictions, nature, united states of america, usa, atmospheric indeterminacy, improvisation, chemistry, physics, observation, prediction, computer programming, digital tools, safety, understanding, phenomena, observable, temperature, air pressure, water vapour, mass flow.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruytert